ant of   Mitton  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William I Moton was born in 1154, in Stapleton, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 2 sons with Margaret Johnson. He died in 1196, at the age of 42."},"et":{"1154–1196":"1154–1196","1154–1202":"1154–1202","1184–Male":"1184–Surnud","1187–Male":"1187–Surnud","1202":"1202","1154":"1154","1187":"1187","1196":"1196","1184":"1184","about 1187":"umbes 1187","Peckleton, Leicestershire, England":"Peckleton, Leicestershire, England","Freckleton, Lancashire, England":"Freckleton, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Stapleton, Shropshire, England":"Stapleton, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1154–1196":"1154–1196","1154–1202":"1154–1202","1184–Male":"1184–Kuollut","1187–Male":"1187–Kuollut","1202":"1202","1154":"1154","1187":"1187","1196":"1196","1184":"1184","about 1187":"noin 1187","Peckleton, Leicestershire, England":"Peckleton, Leicestershire, England","Freckleton, Lancashire, England":"Freckleton, Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Stapleton, Shropshire, England":"Stapleton, Shropshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1154–1196":"1154–1196","1154–1202":"1154–1202","1184–Male":"1184–Décédé","1187–Male":"1187–Décédé","1